        {
            "id": "0af1f72a5afe42318572c",
            "questionText": "A physics student heats a 50 gram metal block to a temperature of 95 $!$^{\\circ}C$!$ and then places it into a calorimeter containing 200 grams of water initially at 22 $!$^{\\circ}C$!$. The final equilibrium temperature of the water and metal is measured to be 25 $!$^{\\circ}C$!$. Assuming the calorimeter is perfectly insulated and no heat is lost to the surroundings, calculate the specific heat capacity of the metal. The specific heat capacity of water is 4.186 $!$J/g^{\\circ}C$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "c24b62de8c514a40beff4",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the fundamental formula that relates heat energy, mass, specific heat capacity, and temperature change. Which one of the following formulas is used to calculate the heat transferred?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "3ed6a9b8-e10e-4b9d-8aee-d243dc6ee1d9"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Q = mc\\Delta T$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Q = m\\Delta T$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$Q = c\\Delta T$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "83743748091349309a9d1",
                    "stepText": "Great, now consider the metal block. Calculate its change in temperature by subtracting the final temperature from the initial temperature. What is $!$\\Delta T_{metal} = 95 - 25$!$?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "70"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "$!$^{\\circ}C$!$",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "3b7f994b-1da0-41f0-80dc-d5f7eabdaf00"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "83dd0a16bf0b49369fef7",
                    "stepText": "Now, let\u2019s determine the temperature change for the water. Subtract the initial water temperature from the final temperature. What is $!$\\Delta T_{water} = 25 - 22$!$?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "3"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "$!$^{\\circ}C$!$",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "3b7f994b-1da0-41f0-80dc-d5f7eabdaf00"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "6f0845b582224ac389622",
                    "stepText": "Using the heat transfer concept, calculate the total heat gained by the water. This is determined by multiplying its mass, specific heat capacity, and its temperature change. Compute $!$200 \\times 4.186 \\times 3$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "2511.6"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "J",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "3ed6a9b8-e10e-4b9d-8aee-d243dc6ee1d9"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "5de6188b36fa40f7b6bd9",
                    "stepText": "Finally, apply the conservation of energy principle. Set the heat lost by the metal equal to the heat gained by the water and solve for the metal's specific heat capacity ($!$c_m$!$). Use the equation $!$50 \\times c_m \\times 70 = 2511.6$!$. What is the value of $!$c_m$!$ when computed as $!$2511.6/(50 \\times 70)$!$?",
